            <li class="flex items-center gap-2"><span class="text-muted">/</span><span class="font-medium text-ink dark:text-on-primary" aria-current="page">Hong Kong Stamp Duty Guide</span></li>
          </ol>
        </nav>

        <article class="prose max-w-none">
          <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold text-ink mb-4 dark:text-on-primary">Hong Kong Stamp Duty Guide 2024/25: Property & Rental Stamp Duty</h1>
          <p class="text-lg text-body dark:text-muted">Last updated: July 2026 | 11 min read</p>

          <div class="mt-8 space-y-6 text-body dark:text-muted">
            <p>Hong Kong stamp duty is a transaction tax that applies to property and stock transfers. For homebuyers and investors, understanding the different stamp duty categories is essential to budgeting accurately and avoiding unnecessary costs. This guide covers AVD, BSD, SSD, Scale 2 rates, first-time buyer concessions, rental stamp duty, and how to calculate your obligation using a Hong Kong stamp duty calculator.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Overview of Hong Kong Stamp Duty</h2>
            <p>Stamp duty in Hong Kong is payable on certain documents of transfer of immovable property or shares. The Inland Revenue Department collects stamp duty under the Stamp Duty Ordinance. In the context of residential property, stamp duty has evolved significantly over the last decade, with the introduction of Buyer's Stamp Duty, Special Stamp Duty, and various cooling-off measures to stabilize the market. These measures apply in addition to the original Ad Valorem Stamp Duty (AVD) and apply to residential property transactions.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Ad Valorem Stamp Duty (AVD)</h2>
            <p>AVD is the primary stamp duty on residential property transactions in Hong Kong. The amount is calculated as a percentage of the consideration or market value of the property, whichever is higher. For most properties, the AVD is capped at 8.5% of the consideration. However, actual rates may vary depending on the Scale 2 rates or the Special Stamp Duty rates that apply. Using a Hong Kong stamp duty calculator is the most reliable way to determine the exact AVD for a specific transaction.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Buyer's Stamp Duty (BSD)</h2>
            <p>BSD applies to residential property purchases made by persons who are not Hong Kong permanent residents, including corporate purchasers. The BSD rate is currently set at 15% of the consideration or market value, whichever is higher. This duty is levied in addition to AVD and applies to instruments executed on or after October 29, 2016. For non-resident buyers, the combined stamp duty cost can be substantial, making it critical to factor BSD into affordability calculations.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Special Stamp Duty (SSD)</h2>
            <p>SSD is designed to discourage speculative short-term trading. It applies when a residential property is resold within a short period after purchase. The SSD rates are:</p>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
              <li>Disposal within 6 months: 20% of consideration</li>
              <li>Disposal within 12 months: 15% of consideration</li>
              <li>Disposal within 24 months: 10% of consideration</li>
            </ul>
            <p>These rates were introduced between 2010 and 2014 and apply to residential properties where the instrument is executed within the specified timeframes. SSD applies to all owners regardless of residency status.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Scale 2 Rates for AVD</h2>
            <p>Scale 2 rates apply to residential property transactions where the consideration does not exceed a specified threshold. The scale provides reduced rates for lower-value properties but increases progressively for higher-value properties. The threshold and rate bands are updated from time to time. You can use our <a href="/countries/hong-kong/property/stamp-duty-calculator" class="text-link hover:underline dark:text-link">Hong Kong stamp duty calculator</a> to verify the applicable Scale 2 rate for your transaction.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">First-Time Buyer Concession</h2>
            <p>First-time buyers may receive concessions under certain conditions. For example, permanent residents purchasing their first residential property may benefit from reduced AVD rates under Scale 2. Some schemes also allow a refund of BSD for first-time buyers who become permanent residents within a specified period. Always check the latest conditions on <a href="https://www.gov.hk" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-link hover:underline dark:text-link">gov.hk</a> before completing your purchase.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Rental Stamp Duty</h2>
            <p>Renting a residential property does not typically attract stamp duty on the rental agreement itself. However, if the rental involves the assignment or tenancy agreement of a property for a period exceeding three years, the agreement may be subject to stamp duty as a lease. The stamp duty on rental agreements is capped and is calculated in a similar manner to AVD but at a lower rate. Landlords and tenants should verify whether the specific tenancy agreement triggers any stamp duty obligations.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">When to Pay Stamp Duty</h2>
            <p>Stamp duty must be paid within 30 days of the execution of the instrument of transfer. If the instrument is executed outside Hong Kong, duty must be paid within 30 days of the instrument being brought into Hong Kong. Late payment attracts surcharges and penalties. Duty is paid by submitting the instrument for stamping along with the duty payable. The Hong Kong stamp duty calculator can help you determine the exact amount before signing the agreement.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Penalties for Late Payment</h2>
            <p>Failure to pay stamp duty on time results in penalties of up to four times the duty payable. The IRD may also take legal action to recover unpaid duty. Additionally, the instrument may not be valid for registration or enforcement in court until stamped. Proper planning and early calculation help avoid these consequences.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">What is the current stamp duty rate on residential property in Hong Kong?</h3>
            <p>AVD on residential property is typically capped at 8.5%. BSD applies to non-resident purchasers at 15%. SSD applies at 20%, 15%, or 10% depending on the holding period before resale.</p>

            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Can I use a Hong Kong stamp duty calculator for rental agreements?</h3>
            <p>Most rental agreements for residential properties are exempt from stamp duty. However, if your lease exceeds three years or involves certain commercial terms, you should verify using a calculator. See our <a href="/blogs/hong-kong-property-tax-guide" class="text-link hover:underline dark:text-link">Hong Kong property tax guide</a> for information related to property taxes.</p>

            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Do I pay BSD if I become a Hong Kong permanent resident?</h3>
            <p>Some first-time buyer schemes allow eligible purchasers to apply for a refund of BSD upon becoming permanent residents within a specified timeframe. Check the latest policy at <a href="https://www.ird.gov.hk" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-link hover:underline dark:text-link">ird.gov.hk</a>.</p>

            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Is SSD refundable?</h3>
            <p>No, SSD is non-refundable. It is charged as a deterrent to short-term speculation, and the IRD does not provide refunds even if the property is resold at a loss.</p>

            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">How do I calculate stamp duty on multiple properties?</h3>
            <p>Each property transaction is assessed separately. Use our Hong Kong stamp duty calculator to model multiple purchases and ensure accurate budgeting for each deal.</p>
